"# Chapter 7 — Constructive Logic and the Curry-Howard Correspondence

Where types are propositions, programs are proofs, and computing is
proving. The single most beautiful discovery in twentieth-century logic
and its consequences for how we think about mathematics.

Two histories, running in parallel from the 1930s. One is the history of
*proof theory*: Gentzen's natural deduction, intuitionistic logic (of
Brouwer and Heyting), formal systems for constructive proof. The other
is the history of *lambda calculus* and *type theory*: Church's typed
lambda calculus, Curry's combinators, later Girard's and Reynolds's
System F.

Around 1969 Howard, and independently Curry (much earlier), noticed:
these are the same object. Every proof rule of intuitionistic
propositional logic is a term-construction rule of simply-typed lambda
calculus. Every proof is a program. Every program is a proof. Types are
propositions. Not analogous — *the same object under different names*.

That correspondence has three names: *Curry-Howard*, *the propositions-
as-types principle*, *the proofs-as-programs principle*. It is the same
thing. And once you see it, you cannot unsee it. Every proof you write
is code; every well-typed program is proof of a theorem.

> **the runtime says**
>
> *This is the chapter where the book pivots. Everything before was
> preparation — logic on one side, lambda calculus on the other. Once
> you see they are the same, half the field of programming-language
> theory rearranges around it. Constructive mathematics is not a small
> corner of mathematics; it is the fragment that maps onto computation.
> If you were going to remember one chapter, remember this one.*

## The correspondence at a glance

Here is the whole thing, in one table.

    Propositional connective       Type constructor
    ----------------------------------------------------
    proposition P                  type P
    A ∧ B (conjunction)            A × B (product)
    A ∨ B (disjunction)            A + B (sum)
    A → B (implication)            A → B (function)
    ⊤ (truth)                      Unit
    ⊥ (falsity)                    Empty
    ¬A (negation)                  A → Empty
    proof of P                     program of type P
    proof composition              function composition
    proof by cases                 pattern matching / case-analysis
    modus ponens                   function application
    conditional proof              function definition

That is the whole correspondence. Every row is a real, verifiable,
formal statement. Read the second column as *if you have a program of
type P, you have a proof of proposition P*.

Let me unpack the most important cases.

## Conjunction ↔ Product

A proof of `(A ∧ B)` is a pair: a proof of A and a proof of B. That is
a value of type `A × B`.

    (conj-intro pa pb)  ↔  (pair pa pb)      : A × B
    (conj-elim-l p)     ↔  (fst p)           : A
    (conj-elim-r p)     ↔  (snd p)           : B

To *use* a conjunction is to project out one component. That is
`fst`/`snd`. To *build* a conjunction is to pair the components. That
is `pair`. Exactly the introduction and elimination rules of chapter 3.

```scheme
;; The proof: A ∧ B → B ∧ A.
;; As a program: (λp : A × B. (pair (snd p) (fst p))) : A × B → B × A
;;
;; Read this as a proof:
;;   Assume you have p : A × B.
;;   Get snd p : B and fst p : A.
;;   Pair them: (pair (snd p) (fst p)) : B × A.
;;   Discharge the assumption:  (λp. ...) : (A × B) → (B × A).
;;
;; That is a proof that conjunction is commutative.
```

## Disjunction ↔ Sum

A proof of `(A ∨ B)` is either a proof of A tagged with `inl` or a
proof of B tagged with `inr`. That is a value of type `A + B`.

    (disj-intro-l pa)  ↔  (inl pa)                   : A + B
    (disj-intro-r pb)  ↔  (inr pb)                   : A + B
    (disj-elim d f g)  ↔  (case d (inl x. f) (inr y. g))  : C

To *build* a disjunction is to tag a proof of one side. To *use* one is
to case-analyse and provide proofs of the goal in each case. Exactly
the disjunction rules of natural deduction.

## Implication ↔ Function type

A proof of `A → B` is a function taking a proof of A and producing a
proof of B.

    (impl-intro (assume A) (prove B))  ↔  (λx : A. body : B)
    (impl-elim f a)                     ↔  (f a)

Modus ponens is function application. Conditional proof is function
definition. This is the correspondence in its cleanest form.

```scheme
;; A tiny theorem: (A → B) → (B → C) → A → C  (hypothetical syllogism)
;; As a program (function composition):
;;   (λf : A → B. λg : B → C. λx : A. (g (f x)))
;;
;; If you have a proof of A → B, a proof of B → C, and a witness of A,
;; then chaining them gives you a witness of C.
```

## Universal quantification ↔ Dependent function

For predicate logic we need one more.

    (forall x : A. P x)  ↔  Π (x : A). P x
    (forall-intro proof-body)  ↔  (λx : A. body)
    (forall-elim p t)          ↔  (p t)

A proof of a universally-quantified statement is a function from the
domain to a proof of the body. The type `Π (x : A). P x` is a
*dependent function type*: the return type depends on the input value.

This is where the correspondence *deepens* — you now need dependent
types (not just simple types) to represent predicates. This is Martin-
Löf type theory (1984); it is what Coq and Agda implement.

    (exists x : A. P x)  ↔  Σ (x : A). P x

Existentially-quantified statements correspond to *dependent pairs* —
the first component is the witness, the second is a proof about it.
The dual to a dependent function type.

## The empty type: no proofs of falsity

The falsity connective ⊥ corresponds to the *empty type* — a type with
no values. If you had a value of the empty type, you could produce a
value of any other type from it (*ex falso quodlibet*), which is exactly
the elimination rule for falsity in natural deduction.

    ⊥        ↔  Empty
    absurd   ↔  (λx : Empty. anything)

Negation is *implication into falsity*.

    ¬A       ↔  A → Empty

A proof of `¬A` is a function that turns any purported proof of A into
a proof of falsity — that is, a function that can never actually be
invoked (unless A has no proofs, i.e., is false).

```scheme
;; A proof of ¬(A ∧ ¬A) — the *law of non-contradiction*.
;; As a program:  (λp : A × (A → Empty). ((snd p) (fst p))) : (A × (A → Empty)) → Empty
;;
;; Read: If you had a proof of A and a proof of ¬A, you could apply the
;; second to the first, yielding a value of the empty type. So the
;; supposition (A × ¬A) leads to Empty; therefore ¬(A ∧ ¬A).
```

## The correspondence changes what proof means

Now for the deep part. In classical logic, `(A ∨ ¬A)` is a *tautology* —
the law of the excluded middle. You can prove it by walking a truth
table: either A is true or A is false, either way `(A ∨ ¬A)` is true.

But under Curry-Howard, a proof of `(A ∨ ¬A)` would be a value of type
`A + (A → Empty)`. That value would need to be either `(inl a)` for
some proof `a : A`, or `(inr f)` for some function `f : A → Empty`.

*How do we produce such a value in general?* We would need to know, for
any A, whether A is true (and produce a proof) or false (and produce a
refutation). But for many propositions, we do not know. Are there
infinitely many twin primes? We do not know. Is the Riemann hypothesis
true? We do not know. If `A ∨ ¬A` is a tautology, we should have a
proof of `RH ∨ ¬RH`. But we do not — because neither `inl(proof of RH)`
nor `inr(refutation of RH)` is a term we can write.

*The law of the excluded middle is not constructively valid.*

That is the observation Brouwer made in 1907 and Heyting formalized in
1930. Intuitionistic (constructive) logic drops the excluded middle. A
proof of `A ∨ B` really is a proof of one of them, not a proof by cases
of the negation. This is what constructive mathematicians insist on,
and it is what Curry-Howard makes precise: constructive proofs are
programs.

## What you lose without excluded middle

You lose double-negation elimination. In classical logic,
`¬¬A → A` is a tautology. In intuitionistic logic it is not. To prove
A, having a proof of ¬¬A is *not enough*; you need to actually construct
A. From ¬¬A you can only conclude ¬¬A.

You lose proof by contradiction *for positive statements*. Classical:
*assume ¬A, derive ⊥, conclude A*. Intuitionistic: this technique
gives you ¬¬A, not A. To conclude A you need a direct construction.

You lose the equivalence `P → Q  ≡  ¬P ∨ Q`. In classical logic these
are the same. In intuitionistic logic, `¬P ∨ Q` is stronger — it lets
you decide upfront which disjunct holds.

The upshot: intuitionistic logic is more demanding. It asks *for a
construction*, not just *for a proof by contradiction*. The proofs it
produces are computationally meaningful.

## What you gain without excluded middle

You gain the *disjunction property*: if `A ∨ B` is provable, then either
A is provable or B is provable. Classical logic does not have this
property (excluded middle is provable but neither disjunct is
necessarily provable for a given A).

You gain the *existence property*: if `∃x. P x` is provable, then there
exists a *specific* term t such that `P t` is provable. Classical logic
does not have this — you can prove existence non-constructively.

You gain *computational content*: every proof is a program. Every proof
of `A → B` is a function you can run. Every proof of `∃x. P x` is a
witness x plus a proof that P(x). This is the whole reason Curry-Howard
matters for computer science: constructive proofs *are executable
programs*. Extract the algorithm from the proof; you get correct-by-
construction software.

## Classical logic under Curry-Howard

You can add classical reasoning to constructive logic by adding an
axiom: excluded middle, or double-negation elimination, or Peirce's law.
On the type side, adding excluded middle corresponds to adding an
operator called `callcc` — *call with current continuation* — which is
a control operator familiar to Scheme programmers.

*Classical logic is constructive logic plus continuations.*

Griffin (1990) proved this: adding call/cc to STLC gives you a term
that has type equivalent to Peirce's law, which is a classical tautology
not provable in intuitionistic logic. Every classical proof corresponds
to a program with control operators.

This is deep. It says: continuations are what classical logic *is*,
computationally. When you use call/cc, you are using classical
reasoning about your program's control flow.

## Program extraction

A significant industrial use of Curry-Howard: *program extraction*.
You prove a theorem in Coq or Agda. The proof, being a program, can be
compiled and run. If the theorem was *for every input x, there exists
an output y such that P(x, y)*, the extracted program takes x and
returns y — with a mathematical guarantee that P(x, y) holds.

Real systems built this way include the *seL4* microkernel (proved
correct in Isabelle), the *CompCert* C compiler (proved correct in
Coq), and pieces of the Coq system itself. The proofs and the code are
literally the same object.

## A worked correspondence: currying

Currying — the trick of turning a two-argument function into a chain of
one-argument functions — is on the program side.

    curry : ((A × B) → C) → (A → B → C)

On the proof side, this type is a *theorem*: `(A ∧ B → C) → (A → B → C)`.
That is one of De Morgan's laws (sort of; the implication version).
Currying is a proof of it, and the proof is exactly the function.

```scheme
;; The proof:
(define (curry f) (lambda (a) (lambda (b) (f (list a b)))))
```

Uncurrying goes the other way.

    uncurry : (A → B → C) → ((A × B) → C)

Same proof, other direction. Currying and uncurrying are inverse
functions, and together they show that `A × B → C` and `A → B → C` are
*isomorphic types* — meaning the corresponding propositions are
*equivalent* in intuitionistic propositional logic. Currying's classical
statement is proved, constructively, by writing the function.

## When you meet a proof, ask: what does it compute?

This is a habit worth cultivating. Whenever you see a theorem statement,
convert it to a type and imagine what program that type is. Whenever
you see a proof, imagine what algorithm the proof extracts.

Sometimes the algorithm is trivial: a proof of `P → P` extracts to the
identity function. Sometimes the algorithm is deep: a proof of
Ramsey's theorem extracts to an algorithm that finds monochromatic
subgraphs. Kleene's *realizability* interpretation makes this fully
precise: every constructive proof has an implicit program lurking
inside it.

Once you have the habit, you look at classical mathematics differently.
Some proofs *do not extract* — they use excluded middle in an
essential way and the resulting theorem is *non-constructive*. Other
proofs *do extract* even though they look classical; the constructive
core is buried but present.

## What Curry-Howard is not

Curry-Howard is *not* the claim that all mathematics is constructive.
Classical mathematicians reason non-constructively all the time, and the
theorems they prove are perfectly good theorems (assuming excluded
middle is a valid inference, which most of the mathematical world does).

Curry-Howard is *not* the claim that programming is proving. Most
programming is not typed with sufficient precision to correspond to
interesting theorems. When you write `(let ((x 5)) ...)`, you are
proving nothing beyond the trivial theorem that Nat is inhabited.

Curry-Howard *is* the observation that there is a fragment of
mathematics — constructive proof — and a fragment of programming —
typed lambda calculus — that are literally the same thing. Programs are
proofs of their types. Types are propositions. When you refine the
correspondence far enough (Martin-Löf type theory, homotopy type
theory), you get a whole new foundation for mathematics that is
essentially computational.

## Variations to try

Take the classical theorem *if not(all A are B) then some A is not B*.
This is a De Morgan's law: `¬(∀x. Bx) → (∃x. ¬Bx)`. Try to write a
Scheme function of the corresponding type. You cannot — this direction
of De Morgan is classically valid but *constructively invalid*. The
converse `(∃x. ¬Bx) → ¬(∀x. Bx)` you *can* write.

Write, in Scheme, a proof (program) of `(P → (Q → R)) → ((P × Q) → R)`.
This is currying's dual and is constructively valid.

## Try this

Pick a theorem from a math textbook — anything intuitionistic will do.
Rewrite its statement as a type. Then try to write a Scheme function
that inhabits that type. If you succeed, you have proved the theorem
constructively. If you fail, ask why. Often the reason is that the
theorem needed excluded middle in the proof — and now you know
something about the theorem that a purely classical training never
told you.

## Closing

Curry-Howard is the discovery that logic and computation are the same
thing. Types are propositions. Programs are proofs. Constructive proof
extracts to executable programs. Classical proof requires continuations.

We now have the framework to make the deep unification that runs
through the rest of this book. Chapter 8 walks through several
worked correspondences in detail — the theorems, the types, the
programs, side by side. Chapters 9-12 explore extensions and other
correspondences: modal logic with types, temporal logic with types,
linear logic with types, category theory as logic.

The whole tower rests on this chapter. If it clicked, keep going. If
not, re-read; a lot of the field became easier once this idea landed.
"
